{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638905"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17745"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72203"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57673"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7163"},{"type":"tags","id":"9924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24420"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72203"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man is found unconscious on the street. He appears very unwell and does not seem to be breathing. You suspect he may have sustained a head injury. After ensuring the scene is safe, you assess his response and confirm he is unresponsive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method to protect his airway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oropharyngeal airway insertion","Jaw thrust","Nasopharyngeal airway insertion","Recovery position","Head tilt-chin lift"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn an unconscious patient with a suspected head injury, airway protection is a priority to prevent aspiration and ensure adequate ventilation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ejaw thrust\u003C/strong\u003E manoeuvre is the most appropriate method to open the airway in this scenario, as it avoids movement of the cervical spine, which may be compromised in a head injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehead tilt-chin lift\u003C/strong\u003E is a common method to open the airway but is contraindicated in patients with suspected cervical spine injury due to the risk of exacerbating the injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOropharyngeal airway insertion\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to maintain airway patency in an unconscious patient, but it should be done with caution in those with potential head or facial injuries. It is not the first step in airway management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharyngeal airway insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is another option for maintaining airway patency, but it is less commonly used in the field and can be contraindicated in cases of facial trauma or skull base fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erecovery position\u003C/strong\u003E is used to maintain a patent airway in an unconscious but breathing patient. However, in this case, the patient is not breathing, so immediate airway management and ventilation are required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In an unconscious patient with suspected head injury, airway protection is crucial to prevent aspiration and ensure adequate ventilation.","The recovery position is used to maintain a patent airway in an unconscious but breathing patient.","Jaw thrust is preferred over head tilt-chin lift in suspected cervical spine injury."],"references":["Ramakkannu K, Theagrajan A, Prabhu M, Ramkumar V. Comparison of Three Airway Maneuvers of Jaw Thrust, Two-Handed E-C Technique With Head in Neutral Position, and Two-Handed E-C Technique With Head Fully Extended: A Prospective, Randomized, Double-Blind Crossover Study. Cureus. 2024 Feb 7;16(2):e53791. doi: 10.7759/cureus.53791. PMID: 38465115; PMCID: PMC10923671.","Austin N, Krishnamoorthy V, Dagal A. Airway management in cervical spine injury. Int J Crit Illn Inj Sci. 2014 Jan;4(1):50-6. doi: 10.4103/2229-5151.128013. PMID: 24741498; PMCID: PMC3982371.","Austin N, Krishnamoorthy V, Dagal A. Airway management in cervical spine injury. Int J Crit Illn Inj Sci. 2014 Jan;4(1):50-6. doi: 10.4103/2229-5151.128013. PMID: 24741498; PMCID: PMC3982371.","Prasarn ML, Horodyski M, Scott NE, Konopka G, Conrad B, Rechtine GR. Motion generated in the unstable upper cervical spine during head tilt-chin lift and jaw thrust maneuvers. Spine J. 2014 Apr;14(4):609-14. doi: 10.1016/j.spinee.2013.06.080. Epub 2013 Oct 23. PMID: 24269083."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T03:07:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T03:08:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10459"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72203"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"me